<br>
Firstly, no-one understands master looting.  I spell it out, in large letters in /g.  You have FV monks using /autosplit on!  Now, you must be roleplaying a darn stupid monk to be doing such a thing! HELLO!  Monk = keep your weight down.  Well, they may understand as they lose 200ac and die ..... or maybe they have not twigged yet &lt;sigh&gt;.<br>
<br>
Worst is good loot drops.  I've seen ninja, then all sorts of rubbish with attempted loot assignments.  The worst thing I've ever heard of is 'I must be the group leader and assign loot because I am a Paladin'  Reaction = /disband (this was experienced by a guildy).<br>
<br>
My guild operates need before greed.  If an item drops that another class can use, you give to that class, normally holding the item a few days in your bank if someone does not log on.  You get DKP back for upgrading other people and your guild grows stronger as a result.<br>
However, does this apply to pick up groups?  Of course not.  Why?  Well, for example, if I take part in a group in CoM then if a Wus drops I'll want to loot even though I have a Ranger and Druid.  Reason is we have a monk that can use it and if not I can sell it.  Also add to that its a rare drop and probably the best thing in the zone and no .. I will not let a monk in my group autoloot it.<br>
<br>
Also, looting for need leaves casters in trouble.  Most armour or wearable drops are for melee classes.  There is much less caster loot to gain.  As such NBG leaves clerics/chanters and shammies left behind (we'll ignore necros for the moment <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> ). Why should they not enjoy the fruits of their labours and gain some unwearale loot to sell on? <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ubjond.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Bjond</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/ezgfx/gicons/white_redspot.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 1016<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(9/30/02 1:26:15 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1477.topic&index=15>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   There is actually more caster loot out there ..</span><hr size=1> .. than there is melee.  Why?  They have all the same slots to fill plus spells.  Saying that one class (yours) gets screwed on loot just shows your own greed or a poor choice of camp spot.  Don't like pickup groups?  Make some friends, join a guild.  Pickup groups in the popular zones suck for the most part.  Go meet people in the hard byog zones.  Those are the fun people.<br>
<br>
Anyway, most of this doesn't apply under 50 unless you have a group of twinks or immigrants that know how to behave over loot.  Lowbies are often extremely gear-hungy, especially around 45 or so.  From 30-45 most make at least one big upgrade a day.  It slows down a ton around 45 and this starts people fighting over gear, since they've recently been conditioned to expect easy gear.<br>
<br>
Anyway, whether you go NBG or not depends a lot on the group.  I will typically avoid groups that I feel can't be trusted to do  basic NBG or that otherwise can't give me what I want.  Usually that's xp, rarely it's loot, and sometimes it's meeting people.  In any of those cases, I'm willing to forgo the secondary reasons for grouping.  It's the groups where the people are fun, the xp is great, and the ML chases you down after you leave to make sure you get your fair share that I like best.  And, yes, they do exist out there even in pickups.  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/usyllestraefv.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Syllestrae FV</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Moderating inconsistently<br>since Jun 2002</span><br>  Posts: 1375<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(9/30/02 1:29:58 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1477.topic&index=16>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Why Need VS Greed Sucks in pick up groups</span><hr size=1>    While I think the example Raine used is kind of stupid (cloth wearing necro in Velks), I do agree with his/her point.<br>
<br>
   In <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> pick-up</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> groups (where you jump in with a bunch of people you may or may not know), I think pure /randoms is the fairest way to distribute all loot, whether the winner of the roll can actually wear it or not.  <br>
<br>
   I've known people who march down to Lguk, win an FBSS, put it on their alt, then march right back down there again and claim NBG, and you'd have no way of knowing that they actually had one unless you were with them the first time they won it.<br>
<br>
   In areas with multiple loot drops (like Highpass) it's best to ask everyone to pick the item they want to roll on (Like &quot;Who wants to roll on the PGT, and who wants to roll on the CDS?&quot;).<br>
<br>
   I think NBG works great when grouping with guildmates, or friends, but in plain old pickup groups I really recommend a /random system.  It's fair.  Even if a necro wins the CC arms, and can't actually wear them, he can sell them and buy something he can wear.  That way everyone has an even shot at the loot, and you don't have to worry about someone faking their &quot;need&quot; for an item.<br>
<br>
